{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_goldman_ver01/data/sn82015313/00383349291/1930102301/0108.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE 6\nGENERAL BOARD\nASKS FUNDS TO\nBUILD BIG NAVY\nFleet Would Be Pushed Up\nto London Treaty Strength\nUnder Plan.\nBn United Press\nWASHINGTON, Oct. 23.-A fif\nteen-year building program to cost\nbetween $750,000,000 and $1,000,-\n000.000 and providing the United\nStates with a virtual London treaty\nfleet In every category except six\ntnch gun cruisers, has been decided\nupon by the navy general board.\nBecause of the British navy's de-\nire to experiment further with the\nsix-inch gun type, action on this\ncategory was delayed.\nThe board was expected to sub\nmit its recommendations today to\nSecretary of Navy Adams, who will\nturn them over to President Hoover\nor final consideration.\n15-Year Program Planned\nSubmission of the proposed future\niavy construction policy to Adams\nalmost coincides with receipt in\nLondon of Japan's formal ratifi\ncation of the London pact, signal\nfor the treaty to become effective on\nthe navies of all its ratifiers. Eng- j\nland and the United States already\nhave deposited their ratifications.\nIt also was decided to spread the\nwhole construction program over a\nfifteen-year period so as not to\nhave the new ships become obsolete\nat practically the same time, as\nwould occur under a five or even\nten-year program.\nRepeated demands by President\nHoover for rigid economy in govern\nment expenditures also were said to\nhave influenced the board\u2019s decision.\nHuge Annual Fund Asked\nCalling for annual appropriations\nby congress of between $50,000,000\nand $65,000,000, as compared with an\naverage of $40,000,000 in recent\nyears, the board\u2019s program is under\nstood specifically to provide for:\nModernization of the battleships New\nMexico. Mississippi and Idaho.\nConstruction of the one eight-inch gun\ncruiser remaning under the fifteen-year\nprogram of 1929 and the laying down of\none each In the years 1933, 1934 and 1935\nas allowed under the London fleet.\nBuilding of several slx-lnch gun cruisers j\nfor experimentation, some to be of the\nhybrid type.\nCompletion of the airplane carriers\nalready laid down and construction of four\nothers to bring the fleet up to the 135,000-\nton quota of the treaty.\nDisposal of enough obsolete destroyers\nto permit replacement by new craft on a\nsmall scale and bring the tonnage up to\ntho limits of the treaty, 150,000 tons.\nRemodeling of the present V-type sub\nmarines to assure the navy of a better\nundersea boat for tactical purposes, and\nconstruction of the three remaining under\nthe V-boat authorization and enough more\nto provide an efficient and modern fleet\nof submersibles. Treaty quota In sub\nmarines Is 52.700 tons, whereas the navy j\nnow has considerably more than this. I\nBritain to Work With U. S.j\nBu United Press\nLONDON, Oct. 23.\u2014Great Brit-,\nam and the United States may work\ntogether to accelerate general dis\narmament when the preparatory dis\narmament commission of the League\nof Nations meets at Geneva next\nmonth.\nPolitical sources predicted today j\nthat the disarmament session would\nreveal a stubborn continuation of\nBritain\u2019s recent foreign policy,\nwhich was first manifest at the Lon-\n<lon naval conference.\nTile labor government's new policy\nlias involved abstension, as far as\npossible, from European entangle\nments and rivalries and co-opera\ntion with the United States when\never possible.\nThus two of the outstanding na\nval powers of the world, backed by-\nGermany, and other nations dis\narmed under the Versailles treaty,\nwill be expected to clash with\nFrance and her military allies.\nFrance Fears Debt Troubles j\nBit United Press\nPARIS, Oct. 23.\u2014Grave fore-\nbodings for the future of post-war\ninternational obligations were ex-\npressed today by the French press\nin connection with \u201cthe continued\n\u2022aggressiveness of German political\nleaders.\u201d\nUnless the League of Nations\nmaterially strengthens its influence\nand the present treaties of Ver\nsailles and Locarno are \u201cirre\nvocably maintained\u201d there is a\nstrong likelihood of trouble in\n\u25a0Europe, according to the Nation\nalists.\nRevision Movement Gains\nI!n United Press\nBERLIN. Oct. 23.\u2014Movement for\nrevision of the Owen D. Young re\nparations plan gained strength in\nGermany today despite official gov\nernment Indications that the cabi\nnet is not at present contemplating\na declaration of a moratorium,\nwhich has been demanded by vari\nous political factions.\nThis was made known despite the\nprivate negotiations in the United\nStates of Dr. Hjalmar Schacht, for\nmer Reichsbank president, who was j\nunderstood to be campaigning for\na suspension of reparations pay\nments.\nWINKLER ADDRESSES\nPARENT-TEACHERS\nrime Among Young Boys,\u201d\nSheriff's Subject Before Women.\nSheriff George Winkler, Coffin\nt andidate for re-election, addressed\nthe Federated Parent-Teachers\nClub Wednesday at School 58.\n\"Winkler was not there for any\npolitical purpose.\u201d declared Mrs.\nClayton Ridge, president of the fed\neration.\n\"I don't think that ten people\nknew who he was except that he\nFas introduced as 'Sheriff' Winkler,\u201d\n(he said.\nWinkler spoke on \u201cCrime Among\nVoting Boys.\"\nThe election is Nov. 4.\nMoney and Grease Stolen\nTimes Special\nMT. VERNON. Ind., Oct. 22.\nburglars who had battered the com\nbination of a safe, stole more than\nMOO from the Davis Oil Company,\nbroke into a <-oa! company office\nbut found no cash, and stole gaso\nIme and cup \u2014xse from the Stan- j\ndvrd Oil Company station. It is j\nbc's:vea several were in the gang I\nand loot was carried away in a\ntntfk.\nLions Strike at Hard\nTimes; Spend SIOO Each\ni Iff\nHI Mi 1 If iff jk\nadfiAAi/flfr dm. f:\nLion Hubert B. Moore, chairman of the Indianapolis club\u2019s business\nconfidence committee, chose furniture for his SIOO purchase. Other\norganizations throughout the country are following Lions\u2019 lead in buy\ning now to boost business.\nDecide to Let Wives Finish\nCampaign to Lessen\nDepression.\nMembers of the Indianapolis Lions\nClub set out to usher in business\nprosperty, but their wives will fin\nish the task.\nMany of the Lions said today\nthey would furnish the SIOO to be\nspent during business confidence\nweek and trust their wives to do the\nbuying.\nSome agreed that the \u201chead of\nthe house\u201d was best at handling the\npocketbooks while others awkwardly\nconsoled themselves by saying that\nthe wives should do it because the\naim of the \u201cbusiness revival scheme\u201d\nwas to spend the money as quickly\nas possible.\nThat the wives did not oppose\ntheir husband\u2019s plan to boost busi\nness by a spree of spending was evi\ndent Wednesday when forty-five\nwives of members surprised the\nLions\u2019 Club by attending its \u201cPros\nperity day\u201d luncheon in the Lincoln.\nA few of the Lions covered their\ndistress with prosperity smiles when\ntheir ladies informed them they\nhad started a shopping tour, but\nwould need slightly more than SIOO\nto finish. The women proudly af\nfirmed \u201cwe are better spenders than\nthe men.\u201d\nIt is estimated the Lions Clubs\nthroughout the country will put\nbetween $1,000,000 and $2,000,000 in\ncirculation as a boost to prosperity\nthis week. The Indianapolis Lions\nwill spend approximately $20,000 of\nthis amount.\nHubert B. Moore is chairman of\nthe business conference committee\nseeking to enlist other clubmen in\nthe spending project, based on the\nidea that business will be stimulated\nif the public buys the things it needs\nand can afford.\nE*nlP* A V rl Q A T 7 TDPIA V mer That WiU Live Long\nA JaSl A I OLTIQ m kJ JT in the Memory of Value Seekers!\nA Gorgeous 25-Piece Set\nof \u201cGolden-Maize\u201d\nDishes Given Absolutely Zi JjmjjjsM\nFREE lllllgl\ndecorated in the modern manner. Make your selection early!\nsee It!\u2014Hear It!\u2014Compare I